“He fails to notice possible danger, and gets too close to animals, even moribund lions,” he said, adding, “This country will miss Mphahlele with his human-like stances.”

The student from the Edward Swartz Educational Complex (ESEC) was attacked on Wednesday after checking cell phones at his friend, Tšie’s, house.

Tšie said, “When I realized why he was so hooked to his cell phone, I quickly picked it up and threw it away.”

Unused to be without a phone or social media, Mphahlele could not argue with Tšie because he was on the phone.

Meanwhile, Mphahlele started staring at the dumb phone as dumb phone watched the phone-owner in a state of amazement.

Tšie went inside the house to get a machete. However, when she and her sister got out, Mphahlele already had a lion out of the safety perimeter.

Tšie asked Mphahlele why he was friends with lions, to which he said he wanted friendship.

She insisted he stop becoming friends with lions and hang out with normal humans like her.

Mphahlele gave a large “okay” as he concentrated on his speech.

Tšie immediately got her machete out and lunged at him.

While she cut the lion, Mphahlele had already bit her on the neck.
